  "text": "is called an elementary interval (in base b). Moreover, for s ∈ N and vectors j = (j 1 , . . . , j s ) and k = (k 1 , . . . , k s ) (where for every l = 1, . . . , s, we require 0 −m . Now let us focus on the case t = 0. Taking a (0, m, s)-net and applying to it a random scrambling of depth m one obtains a randomized point set. Scramblings are defined in such a way that for any scrambling S of depth m and a (0, m, s)-net P , the point set S(P ) is again a (0, m, s)-net. By an appropriate choice of randomized scramblingS one may makeS(P ) to be a sampling scheme. In this case we callS(P ) a scrambled (0, m, s)-net. Scrambling as a way of randomization of (0, m, s)-nets has been studied by A.B. Owen, e.g., in [CITATION_1] .",
